title: Rod Culleton’s Senate career to end as bankruptcy stay closes
text:
Australian politics Rod Culleton’s Senate career to end as bankruptcy stay closes 
Senate president Stephen Parry rejects Culleton’s bid to recall Senate ‘as a matter of urgency’ to overturn bankruptcy finding Senator Rodney Culleton’s political career is set to end on Friday. His former party leader Pauline Hanson says she is pleased to see him go. Photograph: Mick Tsikas/AAP Australian politics Rod Culleton’s Senate career to end as bankruptcy stay closes 
Senate president Stephen Parry rejects Culleton’s bid to recall Senate ‘as a matter of urgency’ to overturn bankruptcy finding   04.44 GMT Last modified on   04.46   Share on Messenger Close 
Rod Culleton’s Senate career will soon be over, with the Senate president, Stephen Parry, preparing to tell the governor of Western Australia the state has a vacancy in the upper house. 
Parry has rejected Culleton’s request to recall the Senate “as a matter of urgency” to overturn a bankruptcy finding against him. 
Culleton, who quit One Nation last month citing “personal attacks and un-Australian behaviour” towards him by the party, was declared bankrupt by the federal court on 23 December, disqualifying him from parliament. Rod Culleton recovering at home after altercation outside Perth court Read more 
The court granted a 21-day stay on the bankruptcy order , which ends on Friday. 
Parry says he is waiting for the federal court to formally notify him of the end of the order’s stay, and once he receives that he will tell Western Australia’s governor there is a Senate vacancy to be filled. 
He has rejected Culleton’s request to recall the upper house to decide on the validity of the federal court’s ruling, saying the constitution gives no discretion to the Senate to disregard a “disqualifying event”, such as a bankruptcy ruling by a court. 
It means Culleton’s career as a senator could be over in days. 
Parry says who fills the vacancy left by Culleton’s departure will be a matter for the high court. That decision will be determined by the outcome of a separate legal matter being heard in the high court over Culleton’s eligibility to contest the 2 July election after a larceny conviction, which was later annulled. 
If the high court rules Culleton’s election was invalid then it may order a vote recount which could result in Culleton being replaced by his brother-in-law Peter Georgiou, who was No 2 on the One Nation Senate ticket in WA, or a candidate from another political party. 
But if the court finds Culleton was eligible to stand at the election there would be a casual vacancy under section 15 of the constitution and One Nation would be able to nominate another person for the seat. Pauline Hanson says she can’t work with One Nation’s Rod Culleton 
When Culleton quit the party last month, Pauline Hanson said she was pleased to see him go, describing him as a pain in her backside .
